### **Convert Markdown to HTML**

Here's a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing html formatted text.

#### **Function Definition**

```cpp
std::string convertMarkdownToHTML(std::string& markdown) {
  // Create a std::stringstream to hold the HTML output
  std::stringstream html;

  // Iterate through each line of the markdown
  std::istringstream markdownStream(markdown);
  std::string line;
  while (std::getline(markdownStream, line)) {
    // Check if the line is a header
    if (line[0] == '#') {
      // Replace the '#' with '<h' + level + '>'
      int level = line[0] - '0';
      html << "<h" << level << ">" << line.substr(1) << "</h" << level << ">\n";
    }
    // Check if the line is a list item
    else if (line[0] == '*') {
      // Replace the '*' with '<li>'
      html << "<li>" << line.substr(1) << "</li>\n";
    }
    // Check if the line is a link
    else if (line.find("http") == 0 || line.find("www.") == 0) {
      // Replace the link with an HTML anchor tag
      html << "<a href=\"" << line << "\">" << line << "</a>\n";
    }
    // Otherwise, just add the line as plain text
    else {
      html << line << "\n";
    }
  }

  // Return the HTML output as a string
  return html.str();
}
```

#### **Usage**

Here's an example of how to use the function:

```cpp
// Create a string containing markdown text
std::string markdown = "# Hello, World!\n\n* This is a list item.\n* And another one.";

// Convert the markdown to HTML
std::string html = convertMarkdownToHTML(markdown);

// Print the resulting HTML
std::cout << html << std::endl;
```

**Output:**

